widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Responsible investment, shareholder activism and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  are all phrases that will put even the most powerful executives on their guard.\par \par \uc2 Ian Jones is one of a growing number of boardroom watchdogs who believe there is more to running a company than squeezing out the last of the profits to bolster executive pay. As head of responsible investment at the Co-operative Insurance Society (CIS) Jones analyses companies in terms of corporate governance.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "We expect the best from the companies we invest in, on environmental and social issues but also on corporate governance," says Jones, 40, who lives in Cheshire. He spent most of his career as a company secretary, at CIS as well as elsewhere, before switching to analysis in 1999.\par \par \uc2 "We believe that the way companies deal with environmental issues or corporate governance is often a very strong indicator of the quality of the management as a whole," he says.\par \par \uc2 The investment arm of CIS, which has Pounds 22bn under management, was one of the principal forces behind a campaign that resulted in the resignation of Stelios Haji-Ioannou, founder and chairman of low-cost airline EasyJet from his own board.\par \par \uc2 "There are instances where we have helped companies to change direction. EasyJet is a good example. Despite having only a small holding . . .we suggested that it wasn't the best thing for Stelios to remain as chairman," says Jones. Fund managers had objected to his position as chairman while also owning, with his family, 58.5 per cent of the company. "We think it's important to remember that it is not up to shareholders to direct the company, but we often come up with an idea which is then acted upon by the company."\par \par \uc2 CIS initiated private talks with EasyJet about its concerns and made its views public at the firm's annual meeting in March last year. Within a month, Haji-Ioannou called a press conference and announced he would step down.\par \par \uc2 "Our relationship with companies is an ongoing process and our experience shows that corporate change can and does occur even after annual meeting resolutions have been defeated."\par \par \uc2 Companies wanting to be seen as socially responsible must not only guarantee boardroom behaviour but also fair employment practices, rigorous health and safety, concern about consumer issues, impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , discrimination and cruelty to animals.\par \par \uc2 CIS is best known for its "ethical" investment funds, but its activity also involves well-known blue-chip stocks whose corporate governance and environmental standards often fail to meet those of the Co-op.\par \par \uc2 Jones defends CIS's involvement with such companies. For him, socially responsible investing (SRI), means "engaging in dialogue with companies to try to persuade them to follow best practice." He believes it does not mean selling shares in errant companies or refusing to buy in the first place, which is the role of ethical investment funds.\par \par \uc2 "We will buy shares in those companies whose activities some investors may disapprove of, but then use those stakes to lobby for change or improved practices," says Jones.\par \par \uc2 "Whilst we don't have a policy of exclusion, we do sometimes realise we're not getting anywhere and we will take our money out."\par \par \uc2 He gives the example of Unocol, a company with operations in Burma, which CIS had particular concerns over. "We engaged with the company by putting forward a shareholder resolution at the AGM but the company did very little. This was a case where we felt that the company was so intransigent that we were not going to get anywhere and ultimately we divested."\par \par \uc2 There are certain companies whose policies CIS will not attempt to influence, says Jones. "With companies whose business is in tobacco, oil or arms, some of the more extreme single issue groups lobby them to abandon their core activities. In 2002 at a BP annual general meeting, a shareholder motion asked BP to stop being an oil company. It's that sort of resolution that gives activism a bad name."\par \par \uc2 Why has there been such an increase in shareholder activism? Jones says fund managers have been getting involved in corporate governance for a while, but their activities are not generally in the public eye. "Shareholders have been active for some time but they often have discussions with companies before going public. Our policy is to improve governance, not hit headlines."\par \par \uc2 He does point out that in the past year activism has been made newsworthy by frustration about the performance of the markets and the way some companies have frittered away their money.\par \par \uc2 He also believes that companies themselves have become more interested in issues of corporate governance. "Companies have a heightened awareness of reputational risk and over the last three or four years have formulated much more definite policies for governance and appear to be more open to engagement than ever before."\par \par \uc2 Companies such as Huntingdon have seen their share price affected by negative media attention caused by animal rights protests. McDonald's, Nestle and Nike share prices have also fluctuated as a result of media attention to their attitudes to issues of equal opportunities, third world marketing and child labour.\par \par \uc2 The reception received by Jones and his team at AGMs is varied. On the whole companies are prepared to meet CIS, but not always willing to embrace change straight away. "But we expect that because change is a often a long-term thing and companies need time to develop a strategy," says Jones. "We just want them to recognise it initially and we can work from there."\par \par \uc2 But times are changing. "When I started on shareholder engagement in 1999, there was a much more hostile \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The attitude of some boards was that it was an act of disloyalty to get a board to change course. It's a very different climate now. It's much easier to get access to senior board members."\par \par \uc2 The cornerstone of CIS strategy is to use its votes at annual meetings. "It's really important to attend AGMs to get an idea of how the board works together. Apart from the odd director who falls asleep or votes against his re-election, we find they are really useful."\par \par \uc2 CIS now publishes its voting records on the website the day it has voted. "This extends transparency to our investors and represents a milestone for the industry. It is investors' money we are using so we think it's only right for them to be able to see how we use it," says Jones. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c41 : \uc2 Management Issues | cbestp : \uc2 Best Practice | ccpgvn : \uc2 Corporate Governance/Investor Relations | c152 : \uc2 