lpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 International laws are needed to control multinationals' operations in developing countries because their voluntary social and environmental initiatives have proved "wholly inadequate", Christian Aid said in a report on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 The development agency uses case studies involving British American Tobacco, Coca-Cola and Royal Dutch/Shell to illustrate its claim that the rhetoric of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  can mask operations that make life worse for the communities in which multinationals operate.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Christian Aid says BAT stresses the health and safety of workers, but contract tobacco farmers in Kenya and Brazil report inadequate protection against pesticides and complain of related ill-health.\par \par \uc2 Coca-Cola stresses responsible use of natural resources but this jars with accusations that its subsidiary in the Indian state of Kerala has depleted village wells of scarce water.\par \par \uc2 Shell says it strives to be a good neighbour, but the report accuses it of failing to clean up oil spills quickly in the Niger Delta and establishing "frequently ineffective" community development projects. The case studies include responses from the companies.\par \par \uc2 "Governments must adopt an international set of standards for the behaviour of companies," said Andrew Pendleton, senior policy officer at Christian Aid and author of the report, Behind the mask: the real face of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which is published to coincide with the opening of the World Economic Forum on Wednesday. "Instead of talking about more voluntary CSR in Davos, governments should be discussing how new laws can raise standards of corporate behaviour."\par \par \uc2 Christian Aid has already called for mandatory social and environmental reporting by British companies. It is one of the non-profit groups in the Corporate Responsibility (Core) campaign, which wants the UK to make directors legally accountable for their companies' actions overseas and allow redress through British courts for those harmed by companies' foreign operations. The government prefers a voluntary approach. Today's report urges the European Union to adopt legally binding human rights, environmental and social standards for EU companies operating overseas.\par \par \uc2 It also says the United Nations should start developing "an international legal framework for corporate accountability" to include key standards in areas such as the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , labour, human rights and transparency. It argues that the recent UN norms on human rights should form the basis of this effort.\par \par \uc2 "Business has consistently used CSR to block attempts to establish the mandatory international regulation of companies' activities," the report says. Resistance to regulation "has left the worst corporate abusers effectively unrestrained and the victims of their actions without adequate means of redress". \pa