in0 \uc2 Surveys WMR1\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PG\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 Page 2\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2004 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 This is the sixth year we have conducted this global survey of Chief Executive Officer (CEO) opinion, and this year we have again achieved interviews with more than 1,000 respondents across 20 countries.\par \par \uc2 The core of the survey remains consistent over time, identifying those companies and business leaders globally that are most respected by their peers and the reasons for those choices. In addition, to reflect the increasingly competitive \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and hence reputation required for companies to succeed, we identified companies seen to excel in areas such as corporate governance and social responsibility.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Firstly, chief executives were asked to nominate which three companies in the world they most respect. They were then asked to select three companies that they most respect in their industry sector in the world. Next, each chief executive was asked to identify which three business leaders they most respect in the world. Each question was asked in previous surveys. In each case, and for all subsequent questions, respondents were asked to give reasons for their nominations.\par \par \uc2 In the past three years of the survey CEOs were also asked to nominate which three companies best delivered on creating the most value for their shareholders. To provide a contrast to CEO opinion, this question was also put to nearly 100 fund managers worldwide.\par \par \uc2 For a successive year, CEOs were asked to name three companies in their country or region that they most respect and three companies that demonstrate the most integrity. Two new questions asked of CEOs this year were to nominate three companies in the world that have the most effective corporate governance and the companies in the world that best demonstrate their commitment to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 To again provide a contrast to CEO opinion approximately 90 media commentators and non-governmental organisations (NGO) worldwide were asked the questions on integrity, corporate governance and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The fieldwork was undertaken between November and December 2003, principally by telephone interview but in some cases by written questionnaire or face-to-face interviews. As in previous years, the survey participants come not just from publicly-quoted organisations but also from large subsidiaries and private companies across the 20 countries.\par \par \uc2 As in previous years, we were faced with the choice of weighting the data by GDP of the respondent's country (the only measure available across all respondents), or leaving it untouched. Once again we decided to weight the data, both to ensure consistency with previous years' results, and to reflect that, rightly or wrongly, there are different levels of global impact achieved by views expressed in different economies. This approach applies to the CEO, fund manager and media/NGO surveys.\par \par \uc2 To ensure that we smooth out any single country bias, we have once again applied a minimum qualification level of five nominations to each table, apart from the World's Most Respected Companies by Industry Sector and within individual country, where a minimum of three nominations was required.\par \par \uc2 Importantly, we have analysed the unprompted reasons given for nominations, providing a valuable insight into what factors drive respect for companies and business leaders.\par \par \uc2 In summary, the methodology allows for an in-depth and credible look at the opinions of global CEOs and other relevant stakeholders. It also provides the ability to track changes in position for companies over time as well as the reasons that lie behind their nominations.\par \par \uc2 * Judith Nicholl is head of research at PricewaterhouseCoopers Judith.nicholl@uk.pwc.com \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i8395201 : \uc2 Market Research/Opinion Polling | i83952 : \uc2 Market Research/Public Relations | iadv : \uc2 Advertising/Public Relations/Marketing\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c41 : \uc2 Management Issues | ccpgvn : \uc2 Corporate Governance/Investor Relations | c11 : \uc2 Plans/Strategy | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trle