alpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Is corporate responsibility a con?\par \par \uc2 There was open warfare this week among what one might call the open-toed-sandal brigade: those who want to see more \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 CSR - the abbreviation used by its growing number of devotees - has it that companies have a duty to act responsibly, not just to their shareholders by maximising profits, but towards society as a whole through care of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , ethical practices, and so on. Some justify this by saying it is self-evidently A Good Thing. Others argue that it is in companies' best interests, since it will protect them from reputational risk and may be linked to better performance.\par \par \uc2 Whatever the justification given, a growing number of companies are signing up. Mary Francis, director general of the Association of British Insurers, which brings together many of the country's largest investors, said in a speech on Tuesday that 80 per cent of FTSE 100 companies now give moderate or full disclosure of their CSR activities.\par \par \uc2 But is all this worthiness worth the paper it is printed on? Not according to Christian Aid, the church-backed charity, which has just issued a report arguing that CSR can become a mere branch of public relations. It supports its claim with critical case studies of three companies at the forefront of CSR reporting - Shell, British American Tobacco and Coca-Cola.\par \par \uc2 It argues that CSR voluntarism is not working and that what is needed is legislation to give companies a duty of care for developing world communities and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 It is fair enough for Christian Aid to highlight the risk of companies just paying lip service to social responsibilities. That does neither them nor anyone else any good. But it is hardly balanced for the charity to conclude that all CSR is bad on the basis of its allegations about just three companies' experiences in small parts of their global operations.\par \par \uc2 And its demands for legislation are a dangerous form of capitalist bashing. There is no good reason for companies to have a greater duty of care than anyone else; it would be next to impossible adequately to define such a duty; and anyway, responsibility ought to involve voluntarism.\par \par \uc2 As Ms Francis put it: "We won't get anywhere if we approach it with a bossy-boots mindset that is determined to tell companies to behave in ways that we personally have decided are good for them. We are not qualified to set absolute standards . . ."\par \par \uc2 The best advocate for CSR - both among companies and sceptical investors, of which there are many - would be evidence showing a link between it and business performance. It so happens that the ABI is promising to publish some next week. Phalanxes of sandal-wearers hold their breath.\par \par \uc2 BBC and privatisation\par \par \uc2 This column has argued over the years for the privatisation of the BBC when its charter comes up for renewal in 2006. But the events of the past year - and particularly the past week - have given me pause for thought.\par \par \uc2 The pro-privatisation argument is that the licence fee is an anachronism in a multi-channel digital age and that vast tracts of the BBC's output no longer conform to the declared rationale for its existence: to "inform, educate and entertain", enriching viewers' lives in "ways that the market alone will not". Much of its coverage is indistinguishable from that available on commercial channels.\par \par \uc2 True, there remain pockets of public service excellence (Radios 3 and 4, the World Service, bits of BBC2). But these could possibly be ring-fenced, allowing a privatised Beeb to compete more effectively on the global media stage.\par \par \uc2 However, the war in Iraq and its aftermath have underscored the public interest role that can be played by a large, independent, non-commercial broadcaster. True, the BBC made a serious journalistic error over Iraq, highlighted by the Hutton report, which suggests a broader sloppiness.\par \par \uc2 But its general standard of neutrality during the war contrasted sharply with the slavish pro-government line of US networks, some of which may be keen to enter a liberalised UK market. And the BBC's willingness to put politicians on the spot - on the Today programme, Newsnight and elsewhere - and engage in political debate is unmatched by the cautious UK commercial channels, with their eye on the franchise and the bottom line.\par \par \uc2 This contribution to democracy - very much in the tradition of Lord Reith, the BBC's founder - arguably outweighs the advantages of privatisation.\par \par \uc2 But there clearly needs to be changes in its governance. The Hutton inquiry has exposed the conflict of interest faced by the governors in both promoting and controlling the organisation. Their responsibility for handling complaints should be taken on by Ofcom, as this column argued when the government was setting up the new media regulator. And to reinforce the BBC's neutrality, responsibility for appointing the chairman and governors should be taken away from the government of the day. But somehow I cannot see politicians voting for that.\par \par \uc2 martin.dickson@ft.com \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i97411 : \uc2 Broadcasting | i9741102 : \uc2 Television Broadcasting | imed : \uc2 Media\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gdef : \uc2 Armed Forces | gdip : \uc2 International Relations | gpol : \uc2 Domestic Politics | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0