 \uc2 There was open warfare this week among what one might call the open-toed-sandal brigade: those who want to see more \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 CSR - the abbreviation used by its growing number of devotees - has it that companies have a duty to act responsibly, not just to their shareholders by maximising profits, but towards society as a whole through care of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , ethical practices, and so on. Some justify this by saying it is self-evidently A Good Thing. Others argue that it is in companies' best interests, since it will protect them from reputational risk and may be linked to better performance.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Whatever the justification given, a growing number of companies are signing up. Mary Francis, director general of the Association of British Insurers, which brings together many of the country's largest investors, said in a speech on Tuesday that 80 per cent of FTSE100 companies now give moderate or full disclosure of their CSR activities.\par \par \uc2 But is all this worthiness worth the paper it is printed on? Not according to Christian Aid, the church-backed charity, which has just issued a report arguing that CSR can become a mere branch of public relations. It supports its claim with critical case studies of three companies at the forefront of CSR reporting - Shell, British American Tobacco and Coca-Cola.\par \par \uc2 It argues that CSR voluntarism is not working and that what is needed is legislation to give companies a duty of care for developing world communities and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 It is fair enough for Christian Aid to highlight the risk of companies just paying lip service to social responsibilities. That does neither them nor anyone else any good. But it is hardly balanced for the charity to conclude that all CSR is bad on the basis of its allegations about just three companies' experiences in small parts of their global operations.\par \par \uc2 And its demands for legislation are a dangerous form of capitalist bashing. There is no good reason for companies to have a greater duty of care than anyone else; it would be next to impossible adequately to define such a duty; and anyway, responsibility ought to involve voluntarism.\par \par \uc2 As Ms Francis put it: "We won't get anywhere if we approach it with a bossy-boots mindset that is determined to tell companies to behave in ways that we personally have decided are good for them. We are not qualified to set absolute standards . . ."\par \par \uc2 The best advocate for CSR - both among companies and sceptical investors, of which there are many - would be evidence showing a link between it and business performance. It so happens that the ABI is promising to publish some next week. Phalanxes of sandal-wearers hold their breath. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\r