\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Business schools are taking the training of ethical managers seriously, says Loredana Oliva. The protagonists ofthe recent financial scandals in the United States were successful students of business ethics in prestigious international business schools. Some even taught business ethics."\par \par \uc2 Those words, spoken by Philippe de Woot, chairman of the University of Louvain in aseminar on social responsibility at Bocconi University in Milan, sum up the scepticism some have towards \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Although acknowledging that scepticism exists, sometimes at a high level, universities have been working to structure the teaching of CSR. The topic is now offered to undergraduates and graduates, with particular attention given to MBA students, integrating it into their programmes.\par \par \uc2 European business schools, who have trailed their US counterparts in introducing CSR into core courses, are now gauging how to bring its themes into the mainstream of business education. The European Academy of Business in Society (Eabis) - initiated as part of the European business campaign on CSR to bring together educational institutions to research and promote CSR in business and education - is at the forefront of this movement.\par \par \uc2 A recent survey by Eabis, with the University of Nottingham and the European Foundation for Management Development (EFMD), reveals the first steps towards CSR made by European business schools. More than 600 European institutions, all of them members of Eabis and more than 90 per cent of them belonging to the EFMD, took part in the survey.\par \par \uc2 The survey reveals that compulsory courses covering CSR are rare. Only 27 per cent of business schools responded that the subject was taught in mandatory, stand-alone courses.\par \par \uc2 However, the Anglo-Saxon world seems a step ahead of other regions. In the UK and Ireland, 15 per cent offer MBA programmes orientated towards social responsibility, and 36 per cent offer optional modules on this theme.\par \par \uc2 In central Europe there are only 5 per cent of MBA programmes with dedicated CSR courses, while in southern Europe 36 per cent of MBA programmes include optional modules. Forty-one per cent of executive courses proposed in Scandinavia deal with CSR through non-compulsory modules.\par \par \uc2 Valerie Gauthier, associate dean of HEC, the graduate business school in Paris, says: "Creating stand-alone courses on business responsibility, or MBA programmes orientated towards business ethics, can be considered a winning choice. But the challenge is to permeate the entire academic curriculum with the theme of corporate citizenship."\par \par \uc2 Rotterdam School of Management focuses on the "how" rather than the "how much" in the teaching of CSR. It considers the teaching of social impact management as an integral part of the accounting and operations management modules that are central to its MBA programme.\par \par \uc2 Mike Page, dean at RSM, explains that ethics needs to be experienced as much as taught. "The student population and the faculty of RSM come from all over the world," he says. "Creating an open debate between them means that each individual is exposed to diverse opinions on business and society."\par \par \uc2 According to Prof Page, this gives constant contact with reality - extremely important for the whole programme, but most of all in elective courses or specialisations on responsible leadership, ethics and sustainability.\par \par \uc2 "To teach the themes tied to CSR correctly it is important to anchor them in the base instruments of management," confirms Kai Hockerts, senior research programme manager and adjunct professor of the MBA programme at Insead, in France.\par \par \uc2 Insead has been active in CSR themes since 1980, and in 1992 created the Centre of Management for \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Resources. Within its MBA core courses in international policy and industrial competitiveness, there is a module on sustainable development.\par \par \uc2 "Today, CSR themes have become fashionable for top managers, and CEOs are deciding policies for responsible business in multinational organisations," says Prof Hockerts.\par \par \uc2 "But it is important that students are aware they will have to practise CSR first-hand when they are part of a business unit, like production, marketing or finance."\par \par \uc2 Business schools are aware that companies can no longer ignore CSR and thus are taking the training of ethical managers seriously. In Eabis's research, certain future drivers are indicated, such as the inclusion of CSR in international accreditations and school rankings.\par \par \uc2 Peter Lorange, dean of IMD in Lausanne, would not welcome such a move. "CSR is a derived 'product' of good teaching and research, practised by involved faculty. It is not a meaningful criterion for ranking on its own," he argues.\par \par \uc2 However, Maurizio Dallocchio, director of SDA Bocconi's Business School in Milan, favours including CSR among the criteria for accreditation.\par \par \uc2 "The adoption of an 'ethical code' by business schools and the evaluation of this code by academies and societies engaged in ethic rating is a practicable road to follow," he says.\par \par \uc2 Peter Lacy, director of Eabis, believes the next 10 years will be very important for schools.\par \par \uc2 "Business schools will have to find new methodologies for mainstreaming CSR in their MBA programmes, with solid programmes focusing on ethics," he says.\par \par \uc2 "If they do not do this they will probably cease to exist. They should be ready to respond to the needs of the market. They have to adopt curricula where the teaching of CSR will be placed among the core courses of an MBA programme." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i9831 : \uc2 Business Schools | i983 : \uc2 Educational Services | ibcs : \uc2 Business/Consumer Services\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | gedu : \uc2 Education | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | c21 : \uc2 Output/Production | gethic : \uc2 Ethical Issues\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360